Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels — For most of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in curbing strong global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero levels and also conducted multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, Bank of Japan, and European Central Bank have also followed the Federal Reserve's lead, each implementing their own version of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
Yet inflation has not been adequately boosted anywhere.
Although these countries are all fighting against deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — — and economic performances — — are diverging.
Currently, the growth of the United States and the United Kingdom is strong enough to allow them to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the Eurozone and Japan are intensifying QE, pushing long-term policy interest rates further into negative territory.
What causes this divergence?
A brief answer is debt.
For decades, the United States and the United Kingdom have had current account deficits, making them debtors, while the Eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, making them creditors.
Negative interest rates benefit debtors rather than creditors, so the negative interest rate policy introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated recovery in the US and UK, but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most creditor countries around the world — — countries with persistent large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland — — have experienced negative interest rates, not only on long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also on medium-term bonds.
This is far from good.
Despite the limited effectiveness of low interest rates, the central banks of these economies still persist with this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring benefits to the economy, they will divert the conversation and refute the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — — which appears flawless at first glance.
But in reality, this argument is full of loopholes.
Basic economics courses have mentioned this peculiar phenomenon called "the backward-bending supply curve of savings": in certain environments, lower interest rates lead to an increase in savings.
This is because a decline in interest rates reduces the income of savers, leading them to cut back on spending, especially if they have savings goals for retirement.
All of this is not rejecting the general rule — — which forms the foundation of modern monetary policy — — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other spending.
However, the impact varies depending on the debt situation of the economy.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what the creditor loses due to extremely low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors will naturally be more than debtors.
For a country with a significant amount of foreign debt, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effects of a lower bound interest rate monetary policy differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important, as foreign asset positions were often small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, foreign asset positions in major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly due to the leverage that caused the 2007–2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage continues to rise at the national level.
Although current account imbalances have generally eased since the start of the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, diverging from deficit economies.
Some major commodity exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, making them a major exception in the differentiation of foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, global oil prices have plummeted, reversing the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export revenues have sharply declined — many countries have lost half — forcing them to run deficits and rely on their large sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodity boom period.
Now, significant spending cuts are inevitable.
Industrialized economies face completely different challenges.
Their problem — — to some extent, a question of luxury — — is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall gains from declining import prices.
However, in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem not to be advancing this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the eurozone.
Although as a whole, the eurozone is a creditor economy, there are also debtor countries within it.
Debt economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have frequent trade surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
However, the current account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are too high, leading to the continued increase in the debtor/country asymmetry.
Most notably, since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated during this period exceeds the historical total before.
According to the current trend, Germany's creditor position may increase from 60% to 100% of GDP.
The central bank governor should be patient.
In fact, the global trend supporting central bank independence is precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to lack patience, struggling with low inflation, despite the output gap slowly closing and the U.S. and Japan achieving full employment.
Central bank governors in debt countries must stop manipulating the economy with more monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
Instead, they should allow recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of falling oil prices to disappear.
ECB President Draghi recently acknowledged that, in today's global environment, the current monetary policy stance may no longer be effective.
But promising more of the old approach is not the solution.
